11. sexaginta milia . . . ceciderunt: i.e. on both sides. Tacitus usually avoids large round numbers. See note Assr. 37, 11. Here his ardent patriotism got the better of him.

12. armis telisque: the specific term is added to the generic and both balanced with oblectationi oculisque. Cp. note ch. 29, 8, and Introd. p. lxviii.
